There can be no question but that the conception os seizing the spirit oi comedy-of the new comedy no less than the old —the comedy ol manners as well as the comedy of scurrilous bur· lesque-and investing it with an easy undress clothing, the texture of which might be varied as the inward feeling changed, was a great advance in the progress of letters. It would seem to be a test of the lawful development osa new form oi composition from an old, that the latter should be capable os including the earlier, as the larger includes the smaller. Or, if we choose to regard satire, as we are fully warranted in doing, in its relation not only to the stage hut to other kinds oi poetry, we shall have equal reason to admire it forits elasticity, as being capable of rising without any ungraceful effort from light ridi· cule to heightened earnestness—passing at once with Horace from a ludicrous description oi a poet as a marked man, to an emphatic recognition of his essential greatness; or with Juvenal from a sneer at the contemptible offerings with which the gods were commonly pro· pitiated, to a sublime recital of the blessings which may lawsully be made objects oi prayer.
